234","–1270":"–1270","1190":"1190","1231":"1231","1283":"1283","1270":"1270","after 1215":"after 1215","1216":"1216","1304":"1304","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1234":"1234","31 August 1231":"31 August 1231","Duston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Duston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Duston, Northamptonshire, England":"Duston, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Dunston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Dunstan  .","variant of <b>Dunstone</b> (see   Dunstan   3).","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Dunstan","meanings":["English:","from a Middle English personal name <i>Dunstan</i> (Old English <i>Dūnstān</i>), from <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’. This name was borne by a 10th-century archbishop of Canterbury who was later canonized.","habitational name from Dunston (Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk), from the Old English personal name <i>Dunn</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. Occasionally the name may also arise from Dunstan (Northumberland), from Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":25,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":34,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William II de Dunston was born in 1190, in Duston, Northamptonshire, England as the son of William de Duston and Mary Wake. He married Mary de Erdington after 1215, in Duston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died on 31 August 1231, in his hometown, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1190–31 August 1231":"1190–31. august 1231","1190–1231":"1190–1231","1224–1304":"1224–1304","1203–Female":"1203–Surnud","1216–1283":"1216–1283","1169–1234":"1169–1234","–1270":"–1270","1190":"1190","1231":"1231","1283":"1283","1270":"1270","after 1215":"pärast 1215","1216":"1216","1304":"1304","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1234":"1234","31 August 1231":"31. august 1231","Duston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Duston, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Duston, Northamptonshire, England":"Duston, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1190–31 August 1231":"1190–31. elokuuta 1231","1190–1231":"1190–1231","1224–1304":"1224–1304","1203–Female":"1203–Kuollut","1216–1283":"1216–